To convert the given physics text into properly formatted LaTeX, we need to present the problem statement and relevant equations clearly. Here is how you can format it:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem Statement}

Calculate the gravitational force between two lead spheres of radius 10 cm in contact with one another. The gravitational constant is given as \( G = 6.67 \times 10^{-11} \, \text{m}^3 \, \text{kg}^{-1} \, \text{s}^{-2} \). The density of lead is \( 11,300 \, \text{kg/m}^3 \).

\section*{Solution Approach}

To solve this problem, we need to use the formula for gravitational force between two masses:

\[
F = \frac{G \cdot m_1 \cdot m_2}{r^2}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( F \) is the gravitational force,
    \item \( G \) is the gravitational constant,
    \item \( m_1 \) and \( m_2 \) are the masses of the two spheres,
    \item \( r \) is the distance between the centers of the two spheres.
\end{itemize}

Since the spheres are in contact, the distance \( r \) is equal to twice the radius of one sphere, \( r = 2 \times 0.1 \, \text{m} = 0.2 \, \text{m} \).

The mass of each sphere can be calculated using the formula for the volume of a sphere and the given density:

\[
m = \rho \cdot V = \rho \cdot \frac{4}{3} \pi r^3
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \( \rho = 11,300 \, \text{kg/m}^3 \) is the density of lead,
    \item \( r = 0.1 \, \text{m} \) is the radius of the sphere.
\end{itemize}

Substitute the values to find the gravitational force.

\end{document}
```

This LaTeX code sets up the problem statement and outlines the approach for calculating the gravitational force between the two lead spheres. It includes the necessary equations and variables, formatted for clarity and readability.

