\section*{Satellite in Circular Orbit}

A satellite is placed in a circular orbit of radius $R$ around the Earth. We will explore various aspects of this satellite's motion and characteristics.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] \textbf{Forces Acting on the Satellite:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item The primary force acting on the satellite is the gravitational force exerted by the Earth.
        \item The equilibrium condition for the satellite in a circular orbit can be expressed as:
        \begin{equation}
            F_{\text{gravity}} = \frac{G M_{\text{earth}} m}{R^2} = m \frac{v^2}{R}
        \end{equation}
        where $G$ is the gravitational constant, $M_{\text{earth}}$ is the mass of the Earth, $m$ is the mass of the satellite, and $v$ is the orbital velocity of the satellite.
    \end{itemize}

    \item[(b)] \textbf{Expression for the Time Period of the Satellite:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item The time period $T$ of the satellite can be derived using the relationship between the orbital velocity and the circumference of the orbit:
        \begin{equation}
            T = \frac{2\pi R}{v}
        \end{equation}
        Substituting the expression for $v$ from the equilibrium condition, we get:
        \begin{equation}
            T = 2\pi \sqrt{\frac{R^3}{G M_{\text{earth}}}}
        \end{equation}
    \end{itemize}

    \item[(c)] \textbf{Conditions for a Geocentric Satellite:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item A geocentric satellite must have an orbital period equal to the Earth's rotational period (24 hours).
        \item The orbit must be circular and lie in the plane of the Earth's equator.
    \end{itemize}

    \item[(d)] \textbf{Period of a Geosynchronous Satellite:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item A geosynchronous satellite has a period $T_{\text{geo}}$ equal to one sidereal day, which is approximately 23.93 hours.
    \end{itemize}

    \item[(e)] \textbf{Radius of Orbit of a Geocentric Satellite:}
    \begin{itemize}
